–1414":"1335–1414","1360–1396":"1360–1396","1280–Male":"1280–Overleden","1290–Female":"1290–Overleden","1414":"1414","1335":"1335","Abt 1330":"circa 1330","1320":"1320","1396":"1396","1330":"1330","1360":"1360","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","England":"England","Hamilton, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Leicestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1330–Deceased":"about 1330–Deceased","1330–Female":"1330–Deceased","1335–1414":"1335–1414","1360–1396":"1360–1396","1280–Male":"1280–Deceased","1290–Female":"1290–Deceased","1414":"1414","1335":"1335","Abt 1330":"about 1330","1320":"1320","1396":"1396","1330":"1330","1360":"1360","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","England":"England","Hamilton, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Somerville","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: of Norman origin, a habitational name from Graveron-Sémerville in Eure (Normandy), from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Sigimar</i> (see   Siemer  ) + Old French <i>ville</i> ‘settlement’. The surname was taken to Scotland in the 12th century by William <i>de Somerville</i>, a retainer of David, Earl of Huntingdon, who became King David I of Scotland.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Somacháin</b> (see   Summers  ) or <b>Mag Shamradháin</b> (see   Somers  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Siemer","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Helmut, Helmuth, Otto, Theresia.","German: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Siegmar</i>, composed of the elements <i>sigi</i> ‘victory’ + <i>mari</i>, <i>meri</i> ‘famous’."]},{"name":"Sommerville","meanings":["Scottish (Lanarkshire): variant of   Somerville   1."]},{"name":"Summerville","meanings":["English, Scottish (Lanarkshire), and Irish: variant of   Somerville  . This form of the surname is particularly common in Ireland."]},{"name":"Simrell","meanings":["Scottish: perhaps related to the Ulster name<b>Sumeril</b>, a variant of   Somerville  ."]},{"name":"Summerfield","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places called with Old English <i>sumor</i> ‘summer’ + <i>feld</i> ‘field, open land’, denoting summer pasture or fields cultivated only in summer, such as Summerfield in Woodnesborough (Kent), Somerfield Court in Sellindge (Kent), and Summerfield in Marlborough (Wiltshire).","English: variant of   Somerville  .","Americanized form (translation into English) of German and Jewish (Ashkenazic)   Sommerfeld  , a cognate of 1 above."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Alice Somerville was born about 1330, in England, United Kingdom, her father, James de Somerville, was 52 and her mother, Lady James de Somerville, was 41. She had at least 1 son with Edmund Willoughby. She died in Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"Abt 1330–Deceased":"umbes 1330–Surnud","1330–Female":"1330–Surnud","1335–1414":"1335–1414","1360–1396":"1360–1396","1280–Male":"1280–Surnud","1290–Female":"1290–Surnud","1414":"1414","1335":"1335","Abt 1330":"umbes 1330","1320":"1320","1396":"1396","1330":"1330","1360